<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 11:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I29d5ed50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>11.</label.designator><headtext>Extrinsic or Parol Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7214fa0682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>11:8.</label.designator><headtext>Subsequent oral agreements</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The parol evidence rule relates to prior and contemporaneous evidence; subsequent oral agreements between the parties in connection with the writing are not subject to the rule.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-3-6" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I257382b074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-3-6</cite.query> provides:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>Parol evidence shall be admissible to rebut an equity, to discharge an entire contract, to prove a new and distinct subsequent agreement, to enlarge the time of performance, or to change the place of performance.<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b55230074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext></para></display.quote><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Parol evidence regarding the modification of written contracts is permissible,[<footnote.reference refid="I7b55230174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] but a writing subject to the statute of frauds cannot be modified by oral amendment.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b554a1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] However, Georgia allows an executory written contract subject to the statute of frauds to be rescinded orally.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b554a1174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] Where parties enter an oral agreement with the intent to later memorialize said agreement, the agreement is valid even if the parties ultimately do not reduce it to a writing, and where they disagree as to the terms reached, it becomes a question of fact for the jury, and summary judgment is not proper.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b554a1274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7b55230074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A subsequent oral agreement may be proved by parol evidence if such agreement is supported by adequate consideration. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="2015666200" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2573f7e274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hernandez v. Carnes, 290 Ga. App. 730, 659 S.E.2d 925 (2008)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b55230174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1960123646" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2574460274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Covington v. Brewer, 101 Ga. App. 724, 115 S.E.2d 368 (1960)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b554a1074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1909012945" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I2574bb3274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hawkins v. Studdard, 132 Ga. 265, 63 S.E. 852 (1909)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1955105409" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2574bb3574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gulf Oil Corp. v. Willcoxon, 211 Ga. 462, 86 S.E.2d 507 (1955)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1967130192" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2574bb3874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sanders v. Vaughn, 223 Ga. 274, 154 S.E.2d 616 (1967)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1965125847" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2574bb3b74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Smith v. Huckabee Properties, Inc., 111 Ga. App. 451, 142 S.E.2d 320 (1965)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1974130077" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2574bb3e74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Payne v. Robertson, Beiter &amp; Conner, Inc., 133 Ga. App. 502, 211 S.E.2d 440 (1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b554a1174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="1948104428" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2575577274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Manry v. Selph, 77 Ga. App. 808, 50 S.E.2d 27 (1948)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b554a1274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017231" w-serial-number="2036574755" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2575a59274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Vernon v. Assurance Forensic Accounting, LLC, 333 Ga. App. 377, 774 S.E.2d 197 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 11:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
